NOTE
====
If you are new to Squid or you are willing to explore Squid in details, please check
my new book Squid Proxy Server 3.1: Beginner's Guide at http://tinyurl.com/squidbook.

1. Requires
===========
  a. squid >= 2.6
  b. python >= 2.4.3
  c. python-iniparse
  d. Apache (httpd) or any other Web Server

2. Installation/Upgrade
=======================
  Installation and upgrade procedure for videocache is same. Installation is as
  simple as explained below. To upgrade, take a backup of your existing configuration
  file located at /etc/videocache.conf and then perform the normal install. After
  installation, reference your old configuration file and set the options in new
  configuration file generated at /etc/videocache.conf.

2a. Installation/Upgrade (using setup file from source)
=======================================================
  a) Untar the videocache-bundle-x.x.x
  [root@proxy root]# tar -xvzf videocache-bundle-x.x.x.tar.gz

  b) Go to videocache-bundle-x.x.x
  [root@proxy root]# cd videocache-bundle-x.x.x

  c) Untar the videocache package.
  [root@proxy videocache-bundle-x.x.x]# tar -xvzf videocache-x.x.x.tar.gz

  d) Go to videocache-x.x.x directory
  [root@proxy videocache-bundle]# cd videocache-x.x.x

  e) Use the install.sh install script to intsall videocache and required components.
  [root@proxy videocache-x.x.x]# bash install.sh

                  OR

    You can use the setup.py install script to explore advanced installation option.
    [root@proxy videocache-x.x.x]# python setup.py install
    Use the -h option to get a list of options available as shown.

  BINGO!! You are done with installation. In case you get any error while
  installing videocache, there will be proper logging in the console.

2b. Installation/Upgrade (using rpm file)
=========================================
  a) Untar the videocache-bundle-x.x.x
  [root@proxy root]# tar -xvzf videocache-bundle-x.x.x.tar.gz

  b) Go to videocache-bundle-x.x.x
  [root@proxy root]# cd videocache-bundle-x.x.x

  c) Untar the videocache package.
  [root@proxy videocache-bundle-x.x.x]# tar -xvzf videocache-x.x.x.tar.gz

  d) Go to videocache-x.x.x directory
  [root@proxy videocache-bundle]# cd videocache-x.x.x

  e) Install/Upgrade videocache using rpm command
    1) To install, use the following command
    [root@proxy videocache-x.x.x]# rpm -ivh videocache-x.x.x-x.noarch.rpm

    2) To upgrade, use the following command
    [root@proxy videocache-x.x.x]# rpm -Uvh videocache-x.x.x-x.noarch.rpm

3. Configuration
================
  Assuming you have squid installed. The following configurations are required
  to get videocache running. Users new to Squid are instructed to stick with default
  configuration as much as possible otherwise you'll be lost in directory permissions.

  a) Restart the httpd service as
    [root@proxy root]# apachectl -k restart

  b) Start/restart videocache scheduler (vc-scheduler) using the following command
    [root@proxy root]# vc-scheduler -s restart

    Use the following command to see available options
    [root@proxy root]# vc-scheduler -h

  c) Depending on your version of Squid, open the file vc_squid_x.x.conf in shipped with
     the software bundle and copy the contents to your Squid configuration file generally
     located at /etc/squid/squid.conf.

     For Squid version 2.x, use the file vc_squid_2.x.conf and for Squid version 3.x, use
     the file vc_squid_3.x.conf.

  Save squid.conf and reload the squid service using
  [root@proxy root]# /etc/init.d/squid reload

  SEE Readme FILE FOR MORE CONFIGURATION OPTIONS.

